# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ashure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The religions of this set share doctrinal, historical, and geographic overlap that contrast them with Indian religions, Iranian religions, and East Asian religions, although some smaller Abrahamic religions, such as the Baha'i Faith, are also Iranian religions.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, are the three largest Abrahamic religions, with Christianity and Islam being followed and adhered to by around half of the world's population.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] However, the term has been criticized by some scholars for reportedly oversimplifying cultural and doctrinal nuances between the different religions.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The term *Abrahamic religions* (and its variations) is a collective religious descriptor for similar and closely related elements shared by Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, as well as the smaller religions such as the Baháʼí Faith, the Druze faith, Rastafari, and Samaritanism.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] It features prominently in interfaith dialogue and civil discourse, as well as academic discourse.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The term appears for the first time in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Although historically the term *Abrahamic religions* was limited to just Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, restricting the category to these three religions has come under criticism.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The late-19th-century Baháʼí Faith has been characterized as Abrahamic, as it is a monotheistic religion that recognizes its own descent from Abraham.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The figure of Abraham is suggested as a common ground for Judaism, Christianity, Islam, as well as Samaritanism, the Druze Faith, the Baha'i Faith, and Rastafari and a hypothesized eschatological reconciliation of the seven religions.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Commonalities may include creation, revelation, and redemption, but such shared concepts vary significantly between and within the Abrahamic religions themselves.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Proponents of the term argue that all seven religions are united through the deity worshipped by Abraham.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Catholic scholar of Islam Louis Massignon argued that the phrase "Abrahamic religion" means that the religions come from one spiritual source.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The modern term comes from the plural form of a Quranic reference to *dīn Ibrāhīm* ("religion of Abraham").
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle, in Romans 4:11–12, refers to Abraham as "father of all", including those "who have faith, circumcised or uncircumcised." From its founding, Islam likewise conceived of itself as the "religion of Abraham".
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Bahá’í scriptures state that the religion's founder, Baháʼu'lláh, descended from Abraham through his wife Keturah's sons.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The appropriateness of grouping Judaism, Christianity, and Islam as "Abrahamic religions" and related terms has been challenged.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Adam Dodds argues that the term "Abrahamic faiths", while helpful, can be misleading, as it conveys an unspecified historical and theological commonality that is problematic on closer examination.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] While there is commonality among the religions, their shared ancestry is mainly peripheral to their respective foundational theological claims, practices, and cultures, concealing irreconcilable differences.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The common Christian doctrines of Jesus's Incarnation, the Trinity, and the resurrection of Jesus, for example, are accepted in neither Judaism nor Islam.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Jewish tradition claims that the Twelve Tribes of Israel are descended from Abraham through his son Isaac and grandson Jacob, whose sons formed the nation of the Israelites in Canaan.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In its early stages, the Israelite religion (Yahwism) shares traits with the Canaanite religions of the Bronze Age; by the Iron Age, it had become distinct from other Canaanite religions as it shed polytheism for monolatry.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] They understood their relationship with their god, Yahweh, as a covenant and that the deity promised Abraham a permanent homeland.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The monolatrist nature of Yahwism was further developed in the period following the Babylonian captivity, eventually emerging as a firm religious movement of monotheism.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] With the Fall of Babylon, Judaism incorporated concepts such as messianism, belief in free will and judgement after death, conception of heaven and hell, angels and demons, among others, into their belief-system.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christianity traces back their origin to the 1st century and refers to themselves as a continuation of Judaism (commonly referred to as the old covenant) initially led by Jesus.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] His followers viewed him as the Messiah, as in the Confession of Peter; after his crucifixion and death they came to view him as God incarnate, who was resurrected and will return at the end of time to judge the living and the dead and create an eternal Kingdom of God.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In the 1st century AD, under the Apostles of Jesus of Nazareth; Christianity spread widely.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Paul the Apostle interpreted the role of Abraham differently from the Jews of his time.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] While for the Jews, Abraham was considered a loyal monotheist in a polytheistic environment, Paul celebrates Abraham as a man who found faith in God before adhering to religious law.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In contrast to Judaism, adherence to religious law becomes associated with idolatry.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] While Christians fashioned their religion around Jesus of Nazareth, the siege of Jerusalem (70 CE), forced Jews to reconcile their belief-system with the destruction of the Second Temple and associated rituals.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] At this time, both Judaism and Christianity had to systematize their scriptures and beliefs, resulting in competing theologies both claiming Abrahamic heritage.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christians could hardly dismiss the Hebrew scriptures as Jesus himself refers to them according to Christian reports, and parallels between Jesus and the Biblical stories of *creation* and *redemption* starting with Abraham in the *Book of Genesis*.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The distant God asserted by Jesus according to the Christians, created a form of dualism between Creator and creation and the doctrine of *Creatio ex nihilo*, which later heavily influenced Jewish and Islamic theology.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] By that, Christians established their own identity, distinct from both Greeks and Jews, as those who venerate and worship the deity of Jesus.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] After several periods of alternating persecution and relative peace *vis-à-vis* the Roman authorities under different administrations, Christianity became the state church of the Roman Empire in 380, but has been split into various churches from its beginning.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] An attempt was made by the Byzantine Empire to unify Christendom, but this formally failed with the East–West Schism of 1054.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In the 16th century, the birth and growth of Protestantism during the Reformation further split Christianity into many denominations.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christianity remains culturally diverse in its Western and Eastern branches, Christianity played a prominent role in the development of Western civilization.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islam is based on the teachings of the Quran.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Although it considers Muhammad to be the Seal of the prophets, Islam teaches that every prophet preached Islam, as the word *Islam* means submission, the main concept preached by all prophets.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Quran also mentions God having revealed the Scrolls of Abraham and the Scrolls of Moses.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islamic tradition claims that twelve Arab tribes known as the Ishmaelites are descended from Abraham through his son Ishmael in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The relationship between Islamic and Hebrew scriptures and New Testament differs significantly from the relationship between the New Testament and the Hebrew Bible.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In the 7th century AD, Islam was founded by Muhammad in the Arabian Peninsula; it spread widely through the early Muslim conquests, shortly after his death.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islam understands its form of "Abrahamic monotheism" as preceding both Judaism and Christianity, and in contrast with Arabian Henotheism.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The teachings of the Quran are believed by Muslims to be the direct and final revelation and words of God.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islam, like Christianity, is a universal religion (i.e. membership is open to anyone).
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Like Judaism, it has a strictly unitary conception of God, called *tawhid* or "strict monotheism".
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The story of the creation of the world in the Quran is elaborated less extensively than in the Hebrew scripture, emphasizing the transcendence and universality of God, instead.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] According to the Quran, God says *kun fa-yakūnu*.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Quran describes God as the creator of "heavens and earth", to emphasize that it is a universal God and not a local Arabian deity.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Samaritanism is considered by some fringe Jewish and Christian apologetics to be a sect which diverged from Judaism in the 6th to 3rd centuries BCE.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] There is growing archaeological, DNA testing, and textual evidence in modern times which has proved the status of the Israelite Samaritans as an independent Abrahamic ethnoreligion and indigenous people of the Levant in their own right.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The evidence has authenticated their claim to a legal religious status.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Some sources consider Mandaeism to be an Abrahamic religion – however, that classification is controversial, given that Mandaeism does not accept Abraham as a prophet, despite revering as prophets several other figures from the Jewish scriptures.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] On the contrary, the Mandaeans believe that Abraham was originally a priest of their religion, but became an apostate from it.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Druze is another religion which emerged from Islam in the 11th century, and hence is sometimes also considered an Abrahamic religion.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Yazidism, another Kurdish religion, is considered a syncretic religion and shares elements with Shia Islam, Mandaeism, Christianity, and Judaism, including a belief in Adam and Abraham.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] It has also been influenced by Islamic mysticism and Gnostic Christianity.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In Yazidism, the prophet Abraham is invoked during prayers before a meal, especially ritual meals.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] A number of sources include the Baháʼí Faith, established in the 19th century, since it historically emerged in an Islamic milieu, and shares several beliefs with the Abrahamic faiths, including monotheism and recognising Jewish, Christian and Islamic figures as prophets.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Some scholars include Bábism, a 19th-century movement and precursor to the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Rastafari, an Afrocentric religion which emerged from Christianity in 1930s Jamaica, is also sometimes classified as Abrahamic, in particular due to its monotheism and use of the Bible as scripture.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Abrahamic religions agree upon the createdness of the universe by God, who is conceived of as eternal, omnipotent, and omniscient.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] All three identify the creator of the universe with the God revealed to Abraham.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] However, they differ on how to conceptualize God.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's utter transcendence and that an intermediary — such as an incarnation of God — is required to bridge the gap between God and humans.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] According to Islam, God is knowable through his creation, metaphorical stories of the prophets stored in the Quran, and signs in nature.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christianity proposes God's personhood in the form of a Son of God as an aspect of the Divinity as formulated in the doctrine of the Trinity.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, God in Islam is less personal than described in the Judeo-Christian tradition, and more of a mysterious power behind all aspects of the universe.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Their religious texts feature many of the same figures, histories, and places, although they often present them with different roles, perspectives, and meanings.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Believers who agree on these similarities and the common Abrahamic origin tend to also be more positive towards other Abrahamic groups.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Religious law in Judaism and Samaritanism commands that males be circumcised when they are eight days old, as does the *sunnah* ('tradition') in Islam.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Despite its common practice in Muslim-majority nations, circumcision is considered to be *sunnah* and not required for a life directed by Allah.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Although there is some debate within Islam over whether it is a religious requirement or mere recommendation, circumcision (called *khitan*) is practiced nearly universally by Muslim males.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Today, many Christian denominations are neutral about ritual male circumcision, neither requiring it for religious observance nor forbidding it for cultural or other reasons.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Western Christianity replaced the custom of male circumcision with the ritual of baptism, a ceremony which varies according to the doctrine of the denomination, but it generally includes immersion, aspersion, or anointment with water.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Early Church, as recorded in Acts 15 at the Council of Jerusalem, decided that Gentile Christians are not required to undergo circumcision.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Council of Florence in the 15th century prohibited it.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Paragraph #2297 of the Catechism of the Catholic Church calls non-medical amputation or mutilation immoral.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] By the 21st century, the Catholic Church had adopted a neutral position on the practice, as long as it was not practised as an initiation ritual.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Catholic scholars make various arguments in support of the idea that this policy is not in contradiction with the previous edicts.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The New Testament, in Acts 15, records that Christianity did not require circumcision.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christians practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Eritrean Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church calls for circumcision, with near-universal prevalence among Orthodox men in Ethiopia.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Many countries with majorities of Christian adherents in Europe and Latin America have low circumcision rates.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In contrast, both religious and non-religious circumcision is widely practiced in many predominantly Christian countries and among Christian communities in the Anglosphere countries, Oceania, South Korea, the Philippines, the Middle East and Africa.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Countries such as the United States, the Philippines, Australia (albeit primarily in the older generations), Canada, Cameroon, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Equatorial Guinea, Ghana, Nigeria, Kenya, and many other African Christian countries have high circumcision rates.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is near universal in the Christian countries of Oceania.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In some African and Eastern Christian denominations male circumcision is an integral or established practice, and require that their male members undergo circumcision.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Coptic Christianity and Ethiopian Orthodoxy and Eritrean Orthodoxy still observe male circumcision and practice circumcision as a rite of passage.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is also widely practiced among Christians from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine, Israel, and North Africa.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Male circumcision is among the rites of Islam and is part of the *fitrah*, or the innate disposition and natural character and instinct of the human creation.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Although circumcision is widely practiced among the Druze, it is performed as a cultural tradition and has no religious significance in the Druze faith.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Some Druze do not circumcise their male children, and refuse to observe this "common Muslim practice".
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Circumcision is not a religious practice of the Bahá'í Faith, and the decision is left to the parents.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Judaism accepts converts, but has had no explicit missionaries since the end of the Second Temple period.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Judaism states that non-Jews can achieve righteousness by following Noahide Laws, a set of moral imperatives that, according to the Talmud, were given by God as a binding set of laws for the "children of Noah"—that is, all of humanity.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] It is believed that as much as 10% of the Roman Empire followed Judaism either as fully ritually obligated Jews or the simpler rituals required of non-Jewish members of that faith.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In the U.S., as of 2003, 28% of married Jews were married to non-Jews.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Many Christian organizations, especially Protestant churches, send missionaries to non-Christian communities throughout the world.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Catholicism have happened at various points throughout history.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions to Protestantism has occurred as well, notably during the Reformation, especially in England and Ireland (see recusancy and Popish plot).
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Forced conversions are now condemned as sinful by major denominations such as the Roman Catholic Church, which officially states that forced conversions pollute the Christian religion and offend human dignity, so that past or present offences are regarded as a scandal (a cause of unbelief).
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] According to Pope Paul VI, "It is one of the major tenets of Catholic doctrine that man's response to God in faith must be free: no one, therefore, is to be forced to embrace the Christian faith against his own will." The Roman Catholic Church has declared that Catholics should fight anti-Semitism.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islam encourages proselytism in various forms.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Dawah is an important Islamic concept that denotes the preaching of Islam.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Da‘wah literally means "issuing a summons" or "making an invitation".
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] A Muslim who practices da‘wah, either as a religious worker or in a volunteer community effort, is called a dā‘ī, plural du‘āt.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] A dā‘ī is thus a person who invites people to understand Islam through a dialogical process and may be categorized in some cases as the Islamic equivalent of a missionary, as one who invites people to the faith, to the prayer, or to Islamic life.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Some pursue Islamic studies specifically to perform Da'wah.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Mosques and other Islamic centers sometimes actively spread Da'wah, similar to evangelical churches.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Others consider being open to the public and answering questions to be Da'wah.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Recalling Muslims to the faith and expanding their knowledge can also be considered Da'wah.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] In Islamic theology, the purpose of Da'wah is to invite people, both Muslims and non-Muslims, to understand the commandments of God as expressed in the Quran and the Sunnah of the Prophet, as well as to inform them about Muhammad.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Da'wah produces converts to Islam, which in turn grows the size of the Muslim Ummah, or community of Muslims.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] While there were instances of forced conversions to Islam, these were neither the norm nor part of a systematic strategy of expansion.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Many Muslim rulers practiced religious pluralism, and the Quran explicitly prohibits compulsion in matters of faith.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Most conversions to Islam occurred gradually, driven by social, cultural, and economic influences rather than coercion.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] However, forcible conversion continues to be practiced in parts of the Islamic world.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Christianity is the largest Abrahamic religion with about 2.5 billion adherents, called Christians, constituting about 31.1% of the world's population.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] Islam is the second largest Abrahamic religion, as well as the fastest-growing Abrahamic religion in recent decades.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] It has about 2.0 billion adherents, called Muslims, constituting about 24.1% of the world's population.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The third largest Abrahamic religion is Judaism with about 14.1 million adherents, called Jews.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Baháʼí Faith has over 8 million adherents, making it the fourth largest Abrahamic religion, and the fastest growing religion across the 20th century, usually at least twice the rate of population growth.
[src:ashure/abrahamic-religions] The Druze faith has between one million and nearly two million adherents.
[src:ashure/adakarası] The grape **Adakarası** received a geographical indication registration (*menşe adı*) from the Turkish Patent and Trademark Office (TÜRKPATENT) with registration number 1323, dated 24 January 2023.
[src:ashure/adakarası] In 2025, the wine **Avşa Adakarası Şarabı** received a geographical indication registration as a *mahreç işareti* (registration number 1735, dated 7 May 2025).
[src:ashure/adakarası] The registration specifies that the wine is produced from the geographically indicated Avşa Adakarası grape and that production stages take place within the defined geographical area on Avşa Island.
[src:ashure/adakarası] Some sources described the registration of Avşa Adakarası Şarabı as the first geographical indication registration granted to a wine in Turkey.
[src:ashure/adakarası] Academic analysis of wines produced on Avşa Island has examined Adakarası grapes and resulting wines through physical and chemical measurements, including acidity and alcohol ranges across different producers and wine styles.
[src:ashure/adakarası] The official geographical indication specification for Avşa Adakarası Şarabı describes typical chemical parameters (including alcohol and total acidity ranges) and links the wine’s style to the grape variety and Avşa Island’s local growing conditions.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Kebabs are usually made out of ground lamb meat and tail fat, though there are many regional variations.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Kebabs are fairly common in the area from Mersin in Turkey to Kirkuk in Iraq, and includes Aleppo in Syria.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] According to many authors, this kebab was born out of a fusion of Turkish and Arab cultures.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Birecik, once an important locality in the Eyalet of Aleppo, is said to be the creator of this very kind of kebab.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The version prepared and consumed today in the province of Adana also has a history rooted in the modern Turkish culture, only to receive a "Controlled Designation of Origin" in February 2005, after subsequent legal trials.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] According to the Patent Registrar, an original *Adana kebabı* is made only by a vendor who has successfully passed an inspection conducted on the spot by the Adana Chamber of Commerce.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The *kıyma kebabı* is still prepared in its historical location.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Similar dishes are prepared in neighboring zones of Turkey, Syria and Iraq, where the meat is hand-ground with the addition of tail fat and occasionally a non-spicy capsicum.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] New variants of the kıyma kebabı, not protected under the same patents, have been enjoyed since the 1950s, in communities in the former Ottoman Empire territories, including Istanbul, Baghdad, and Damascus.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] According to the Designation of Origin, Adana kebabı is made from the meat of a male lamb that is younger than one year of age.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The animal has to be grown in its natural environment and fed with the local flora.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The meat should then be cleansed of its silverskin, nerves and internal fat.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] After the cleansing, it should be cut into rough chunks and, along with tail fat at a proportion of one to five, rested for a day.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The next day, the rested meat and fat must be ground by hand, using a crescent-shaped iron cleaver known as the *zırh*.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Only sweet red peppers (also hand-chopped with the *zırh*) and salt should be added.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The Designation of Origin also authorizes, "under certain circumstances", the addition of spicy green capsicum and fresh garlic cloves.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The meat is then thoroughly kneaded together with the fat, the salt and the additional ingredients until reaching a homogenous consistency.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] After reaching homogeneity, the mixture is placed on iron skewers that are 0.5 cm thick, 3 cm wide and anywhere from 90 to 120 cm long.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] One portion of *Adana kebabı* is typically 180 grams of meat on one skewer.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] A "*portion-and-half"*, impaled on slightly wider skewers can not include less than 270 grams, as per the designation label.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] A little water allows the minced meat to adhere better to the skewer, which is the hardest step in the making of this kebab.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] If not done properly by an *Usta*, the meat will separate from the skewer during roasting.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The Turkish word "Usta" derives from the Persian "Ostad" (أستاد) originally meaning "Master" but also now a common honorific to show deference to someone's expertise.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The impaled skewers are roasted over flame-less coals of oak wood.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] When the meat turns dark brown, it is ready.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The skewers are frequently turned during this process.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The melting fat is collected on flatbread by pressing pieces of flatbread against the meat as it roasts; this also serves to heat the bread.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The kebab is commonly served on a plate, as a *porsiyon*, or wrapped in flatbread, as a *dürüm*.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The kebab is served over the flatbread used to catch the drippings.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] It is accompanied by roasted tomatoes, green or red peppers and julienned onions with parsley and sumac.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Many restaurants around Adana will also bring hot hummus with butter topped with pastırma on the side.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The way to eat *porsiyon* is to skin and crush the charred tomatoes and peppers into a paste, put them in a piece of flatbread with part of the kebab, topped by a generous pinch of the onion-sumac-parsley mixture, and wrap the whole thing into a few small thick dürüms.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Ayran and salgam are two staple beverages consumed with kebab in daytime.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] On hot summer evenings, ice-cold rakı alongside salgam is often preferred.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Ayran is more commonly consumed with dürüm compared to the Şalgam.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Many variations of the *kıyma kebabı*, all based on hand-chopped lamb meat and tail fat, are found around the Cilician and Mesopotamian parts of the former Ottoman Empire.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Adana kebab, has been celebrated as a festival in Adana since 2010.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] Adana Kebab and Şalgam Festival, emerged from a hundred-year tradition of enjoying kebab, with liver, şalgam and rakı.
[src:ashure/adana-kebabı] The event turned into a nationwide popular street festival, street musicians playing drums and zurna, entertain visitors all night long at the second Saturday night of every December.
[src:ashure/ailazan] To prepare ailazan, peeled eggplants are sliced into rounds, salted, and left to rest for 10–15 minutes.
[src:ashure/ailazan] The prepared eggplants are placed in a pot along with vegetable oil, peeled and diced potatoes, bell peppers, finely chopped onions, trimmed and chopped green beans, diced tomatoes, and coarsely chopped herbs.
[src:ashure/ailazan] A second layer of vegetables and herbs is added in the same order, salted again, topped with herbs, drizzled with vegetable oil, and a small amount of water is added.
[src:ashure/ailazan] The dish is covered with a rinsed plate and a lid, then stewed over low heat until fully cooked.
[src:ashure/ajapsandal] It consists of onion, eggplant, tomato and bell pepper grilled, stewed, or fried in vegetable oil and seasoned with garlic, basil, coriander leaves, parsley and other seasoning.
[src:ashure/ajapsandal] Sometimes potato, chili pepper and carrots are added although traditional recipes do not include them.
[src:ashure/ajapsandal] This dish exists under different names in many Caucasian and Turkic-speaking peoples' cuisines.
[src:ashure/ajapsandal] The European counterpart of this dish is vegetable sauté or a ratatouille.
[src:ashure/ajapsandal] However, ajapsandali is typically served cold.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] There are many national and regional variations, as well as vegetable and uncooked versions.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Shapes vary and include balls, patties, and cylinders.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Sizes vary from that of a golf ball to that of an orange.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In English, *kofta* is a loanword from the Hindi-Urdu कोफ़्ता / کوفتہ and Persian کوفته *kofta* meaning *pounded meat*.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] The earliest extant use of the word in the Urdu language is attested in Mulla Nusrati's *ʿAlī Nāma* (1665).
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] It was first used in English in *Qanoon-e-Islam* (1832), and then by James Wise in 1883.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] The languages of the region of the kofta's origin have adopted the word with minor phonetic variations.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In other languages, similar foods are called croquettes, dumplings, meatballs, rissoles, and turnovers.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] The ancient Roman cookbook *Apicius* included many meatball-type recipes.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] The first appearance of recipes for kofta are in the earliest Arab cookbooks; Kofta were also found in the Byzantine Empire.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] The earliest recipes are for large ground lamb meatballs triple-glazed in a mixture of saffron and egg yolk.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] This glazing method spread to the West, where it is referred to as "gilding" or "endoring".
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Koftas moved to India; according to Alan Davidson, Nargisi kofta was served at the Mughal court.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Koftas are found from the Indian subcontinent through Central Asia, the Middle East, the Balkans, and northern Africa.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Koftas are found in the traditional cuisines of Armenia, Afghanistan, Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Georgia, Lebanon, Palestine, Syria, Egypt, Greece, India, Iran, Morocco, Pakistan, Romania, Serbia, North Macedonia, and Turkey.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Kofta is also a popular dish among Kurdish people and Assyrian people.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In Turkey, it is "a preferred offering at communal gatherings of all kinds", according to Engin Akın.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In Armenia and Azerbaijan, it is, along with dolma, lavash, harissa, kebabs, and pahlava, a dish of "clearly symbolic ethnic significance" often argued over by gastronationalists attempting to claim it as one of their own country's traditional dishes that has been co-opted by the other country.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Meat is mixed with spices and often other ingredients such as rice, bulgur, vegetables, or eggs to form a paste.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Often added into the kofta mixture are nuts, cheese, or eggs.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] They can be grilled, fried, steamed, poached, baked, or marinated, and may be served with a rich spicy sauce or in a soup or stew.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Koftas are sometimes made from fish or vegetables or even cottage cheese rather than red meat.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Some versions are stuffed with nuts, cheese, or eggs.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Generally the size can vary from the "size of an orange to the size of a golf ball", although *tabriz köftesi*, the largest, average 20 centimetres (8 in) in diameter.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] They can be shaped in various forms including patties, balls, or cylinders.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] A Levantine version, pronounced *kafta* /ˈkɑːftə/, is typically made with minced beef or lamb, mixed with onion, parsley, and spices.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] It can be shaped into cylinders, patties, or balls, and grilled, baked, or pan-fried, served with sauces, dips, or flatbreads.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Variants include Arayes , a Levantine dish made from pita bread that is stuffed with kufta and then grilled.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In Iranian cuisine there are Koofteh Berenji, Koofteh Hamedani, Koofteh Nar, Koofteh Tabrizi and Koofteh Shirin-e Kermanshahi variants.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Azerbaijani cuisine has Tabriz köftesi, with an unusually large diameter of some 20 centimetres (8 in).
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Bulgarian cuisine has Tatarsko kyufte, a Tatar version.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Greek cuisine has tomatokeftedes, a vegetarian version with tomatoes, and *kolokithokeftedes*, with courgettes and feta cheese. Çiğ köfte is a Turkish and Armenian version made with bulgur and raw meat.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In Kurdish cuisine there is doughawa, though it can be stuffed with meat; the kufta is usually stuffed with fried onions and eggs, while the kofta itself is in yogurt soup.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] In the Indian subcontinent, variants include Kofte chawal, with meat or vegetable balls in a curry sauce, served with rice.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Variations use different ingredients for the balls, such as paneer, bottle gourd, chicken or mutton.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Other Indian versions are Malai kofta and Nargisi kofta with a hard-boiled egg wrapped in the kofta mixture.
[src:ashure/akçaabat-meatballs] Historically, Pishtha meatballs were mentioned in a Sanskrit text on medicine, the *Sushruta Samhita*.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] Alani consists of peaches strung together on a thread and dried in the sun, with a walnut-based filling placed inside.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] In some variations, figs are used instead of peaches.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] The preparation involves several stages: peeling the peaches, fumigating them with sulfur, drying, removing the pits, stuffing with the nut mixture, and drying again.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] After the initial drying, the peaches are filled with the nut mixture, gently flattened, and strung on threads for final air-drying.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] Alani is a seasonal delicacy typically prepared in late spring and early summer, during the peach harvest.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] Despite the increasing use of modern preservation methods such as freezing, alani remains a staple on local markets.
[src:ashure/alani-dried-fruit] However, traditional methods are gradually being replaced by faster, more industrial processes, threatening the preservation of original recipes and artisanal skills.
[src:ashure/ashure] In the Balkans and Turkey, Muslims make the dish during the month of Muharram in which the Day of Ashura takes place.
[src:ashure/ashure] Armenians make it as a Christmas pudding and for New Year's celebrations, where it is a centerpiece, Sephardic Jews prepare the dish to celebrate the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:ashure/ashure] In some Jewish, Christian, and Muslim traditions, a similar dish is prepared to commemorate a child's first tooth, or the passing of a family member.
[src:ashure/ashure] For the people of the ancient Near East, foods composed of boiled whole grains came to be associated with spring and harvest rites since ancient times.
[src:ashure/ashure] This association spread to Asia, Europe, and Africa.
[src:ashure/ashure] Rites related with Tammuz, the Babylonian god of wheat and fertility, were recorded as late as the 10th century by an Arab traveler who wrote about boiled wheat among the dishes consumed at a pagan celebration held at Harran.
[src:ashure/ashure] Jews, Christians and Muslims have all consumed boiled wheat in a variety of ways under various names for millennia.
[src:ashure/ashure] These dishes have been sweetened in various ways with sugar, fruit molasses, and dried fruits.
[src:ashure/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Ararat, the family of Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:ashure/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding and that "pudding" is now called *anoushabour*.
[src:ashure/ashure] Armenians make anoushabur to commemorate this event, but also other events.
[src:ashure/ashure] After a baby is born, Armenian families observe a period of seclusion for up to 40 days, culminating in a baptism ceremony (knunk).
[src:ashure/ashure] In general, Armenians enjoy anoushabur as a part of festive spreads.
[src:ashure/ashure] Armenian sources note it was cleverly used to maintain the fast, yet celebrate Christmas eve with a sweet treat.
[src:ashure/ashure] It’s also used in thanksgiving offerings, during weddings or house blessings.
[src:ashure/ashure] Sharing Anoushabur is a gesture of communal warmth, linking family, faith, and gratitude.
[src:ashure/ashure] Anoushabur is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:ashure/ashure] Since Armenians serve this pudding during Christmas (6 January) and on New Year's Eve (Armenians of Jerusalem celebrate it at 13 January), it is sometimes called "Armenian Christmas Pudding".
[src:ashure/ashure] This traditional Armenian sweet porridge is made from wheat or barley, dried fruits (such as apricots, raisins, and prunes), sugar, spices (like vanilla and cinnamon) and nuts (almonds and pistachios are most common).
[src:ashure/ashure] The grains are simmered until tender, then combined with the fruits and nuts, then sweetened, and flavored with rose water and the spices.
[src:ashure/ashure] Anoushabur may be garnished with pomegranate seeds, dried fruits and cinnamon.
[src:ashure/ashure] The pudding may be accompanied by multiple Armenian desserts and nuts, such as almonds or pistachios.
[src:ashure/ashure] Anoushabur (անուշապուր) is a compound Armenian word.
[src:ashure/ashure] "Anoush" (անուշ) means sweet and "Abur" (ապուր) means soup or porridge, so the word Anoushabur literally means "Sweet soup" or "Sweet porridge".
[src:ashure/ashure] According to one tradition, it is claimed that when the ark came to rest on Mount Cudi or Mount Ararat, the family of Nuh or Noah celebrated with a special dish.
[src:ashure/ashure] Since their supplies were nearly exhausted, what was left (primarily grains, dried fruits and the like) was cooked together to form a pudding, what is now called *ashure*.
[src:ashure/ashure] Turkish families make ashure pudding to commemorate this event.
[src:ashure/ashure] Ashure is distributed to the poor, as well as to neighbors, friends and relatives.
[src:ashure/ashure] According to a late Ottoman writer, passages from the Quran were spoken over the cauldron of cooked aşure in memory of deceased family members before it was served to neighbors, suggesting that for certain Sunni families the meal had a connection to remembering the deceased.
[src:ashure/ashure] Today, a dish akin to this is prepared to honor a child's first tooth.
[src:ashure/ashure] According to the Ottoman historian Ahmed Cavid (d.
[src:ashure/ashure] 1803), women gave it away to loved ones, friends, and the impoverished as a gesture of gratitude for the child's survival of the difficult first year of life.
[src:ashure/ashure] In Turkey and many other Middle Eastern countries, this tradition is still common among Christians, Jews, and Muslims.
[src:ashure/ashure] The dish can be either sweet or savory and is known in Turkey as diş buğday ('tooth wheat').
[src:ashure/ashure] Aşure is also made during the Hıdırellez spring celebration, which is the occasion where it is most similar to its ancient pagan roots.
[src:ashure/ashure] Sephardic Jews prepare Ashure, also known as "*trigo koço*", for the Jewish holiday of Tu BiShvat.
[src:ashure/ashure] It is made out of boiling wheat grains combined with sugar, crushed walnuts, and cinnamon.
[src:ashure/ashure] According to Aylin Öney Tan, this practice may have originated from early Jewish communities in Anatolia during the Byzantine period rather than being brought to Ottoman Turkey by Sephardic Jews who settled there following their expulsion from Spain and Portugal in the late 15th century.
[src:ashure/ashure] Several Jewish communities prepare Ashura, also known as *b'Lila*, to celebrate a child's first tooth.
[src:ashure/ashure] This dish is prepared in Bosnia and Bulgaria under the names hašure and ashoure, respectively.
[src:ashure/ashure] Ashure porridge does not have a single recipe, as recipes vary between regions and families.
[src:ashure/ashure] Traditionally, it is said to have at least seven ingredients.
[src:ashure/ashure] Some say at least ten ingredients must be used, in keeping with the theme of "tenth", while Alevis always use twelve.
[src:ashure/ashure] Among these are wheat, barley, rice, white beans, chickpeas, pekmez, date molasses, pomegranate molasses, beet juice, dried fruits like dates, raisins, currants, apricots, figs, apples and nuts like pistachios, almonds, hazelnuts, walnuts, pine nuts and sesame seeds.
[src:ashure/ashure] However, many renditions add orange, lemon and lime peel to add depth to the pudding.
[src:ashure/ashure] Anise seed, black cumin seeds, prunus mahaleb, pomegranate arils, cardamom, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, allspice and desiccated or shredded coconut may be used as garnish, and some variations are flavored with anise liqueur, rose water and/or orange blossom water.
[src:ashure/ashure] The word Ashure comes from the Arabic word "Ashura" (Arabic: عَاشُوْرَاء **ʿĀshūrāʾ**), meaning 'tenth'.
